{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"43514487-9d88-46ae-b626-327ee858868c","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical flow:**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| Switched away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| Switched back | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` fires only on iOS/Mac Catalyst (use it to save state). On Android/Windows, `Stopped` is the equivalent signal.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1be37a5b-5fe7-4601-bbde-22e62c441a02","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about subscribing to Window lifecycle events in a .NET MAUI app for debugging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI that I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Window` class exposes several lifecycle events that correspond to the app's visibility and state transitions. Let me provide a concise, helpful answer.\n\nThe Window lifecycle events in .NET MAUI are:\n- `Created` - window is created\n- `Activated` - window gains focus\n- `Deactivated` - window loses focus\n- `Stopped` - window is no longer visible\n\n\n- `Resumed` - window becomes visible again after being stopped\n- `Destroying` - window is being destroyed\n- `Backgrounding` - available on iOS and Mac Catalyst when the window enters the background\n\nI'll show how to subscribe to these events with a practical example.","outputTokens":568,"requestId":"5034:26727D:1B0D18E:1E135DF:69FA904F"},"id":"195efd95-cf79-4c5d-a45e-a990bef40634","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:50:33.605Z","parentId":"2e37d78c-252b-40a7-bc1b-f09fbb367692"}
